==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Florentine
<hw>Flor"en*tine</hw> <pr>(? ⟦or⟧ ?; 277)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>Florentinus</ets>, fr. <ets>Florentia</ets> Florence: cf. F.
<ets>florentin</ets>.]</ety> <def>Belonging or relating to Florence, in
Italy.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Florentine mosaic</b></col>, <cd>a mosaic of hard or
semiprecious stones, often so chosen and arranged that their natural
colors represent leaves, flowers, and the like, inlaid in a background,
usually of black or white marble.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Florentine</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Florentine
<hw>Flor"en*tine</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A native or
inhabitant of Florence, a city in Italy.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A kind of silk.</def> <rj><au>Knight.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A kind of pudding or tart; a kind of meat pie.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Stealing custards, tarts, and <qex>florentines</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Beau. & Fl.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Florescence</ent>⟦br⟧
